s","6 ATP molecules","8 ATP molecules","10 ATP molecules"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe net yield of \u003Cstrong\u003E2 ATP molecules\u003C/strong\u003E from glycolysis represents the balance between ATP consumption and production. In the initial steps, 2 ATP molecules are consumed to phosphorylate glucose and fructose-6-phosphate. Later steps generate 4 ATP molecules through substrate-level phosphorylation, resulting in a net gain of 2 ATP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile the ATP yield from glycolysis is modest, this pathway is essential as it can occur without oxygen and provides pyruvate for other metabolic pathways.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Glycolysis has a net ATP yield of 2 molecules because it consumes 2 ATP and produces 4 ATP during glucose metabolism.","Glycolysis is an anaerobic process occurring in the cell cytoplasm that breaks down glucose to pyruvate.","The ATP generated in glycolysis comes from substrate-level phosphorylation reactions."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64879"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17511"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64879","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64879"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-15T09:38:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-15T09:39:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10201"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79575"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updat